The Essenes, Qumran Sect, and Jesus movement all had an ideal of \textbf{communal property}.  This ideal may not have been fully practiced by all.  This may sound like communism, but there is a big difference between voluntary membership in an organization and government control of the means of production.  For the Jewish sects, communal equality seems to have been motivated by charity, contempt for wealth, and rejection of earthly concerns. 
\paragraph[{The Essenes according to Josephus}]{The Essenes according to Josephus}\par

\begin{quote}
These men are despisers of riches, and so very communicative as raises our admiration.  Nor is there anyone to be found among them who has more than another; for it is a law among them, that those who come to them must let what they have be common to the whole order,—insomuch that among them all there is no appearance of poverty or excess of riches, but everyone’s possessions are intermingled with everyone’s possessions; and so there is, as it were, one patrimony among all the brethren.  (Josephus, \textup{\textit{The Jewish Wars}} 2.122)
\end{quote}
 Josephus goes on to describe the rule of hospitality that traveling members are welcome by other communities of the sect wherever they go.  Hence, they have no need to carry anything with them (or pay baggage fees). 
\paragraph[{The Community Rule of the Qumran Sect (Yahad)}]{The Community Rule of the Qumran Sect (Yahad)}\par
The Qumran Sect had a long procedure for initiating new members.  After one year the initiate would hand over his property, but it would be kept separate in case things didn’t work out.  After the second year the property was permanently mixed together. 
\begin{quote}
If anyone of Israel volunteers for enrollment in the party of the \textit{Yahad}…  [After one year] they shall also take steps to \textbf{incorporate his property},  putting it under the authority of the Overseer together with that of the general membership,  and keeping an account of it—but it shall not yet be disbursed along with that of the general membership.  The initiate is not to touch the drink of the general membership prior to passing a second year among the men of the \textit{Yahad}.  When that second year has passed, the general membership shall review his case.  If it be ordained for him to proceed to full membership in the \textit{Yahad}, they  shall enroll him at the appropriate rank among his brothers for discussion of the Law, jurisprudence, participation in pure meals and \textbf{admixture of property}.  Thenceforth the \textit{Yahad} may draw upon his counsel and judgement.  (Qumran Cave 1 Community Rule, Column 6)
\end{quote}

\paragraph[{The Jesus Movement}]{The Jesus Movement}\par
The Jesus Movement held a similar ideal, but it was not difficult to join, and membership was not limited to those Jewish by birth.  In a society with great disparity of wealth, for every one rich person you can convince to live simply you can provide economic security to ten desperately poor.  This appeal is believed to have contributed to the spread of the Movement. 
\begin{quote}
All who believed were together and had all things in common; they would sell their property and possessions and divide them among all according to each one’s need.  Every day they devoted themselves to meeting together in the temple area and to breaking bread in their homes.  (Acts 2:44–46)
\end{quote}

\begin{quote}
The community of believers was of one heart and mind, and no one claimed that any of his possessions was his own, but they had everything in common.  With great power the apostles bore witness to the resurrection of the Lord Jesus, and great favor was accorded them all.  There was no needy person among them, for those who owned property or houses would sell them, bring the proceeds of the sale, and put them at the feet of the apostles, and they were distributed to each according to need.  (Acts 4:32–35)
\end{quote}

\begin{quote}
Share all things with your brother and do not say that anything is your own.  (Didache 4:8 [not in the New Testament but very early])
\end{quote}

\subsubsection[{Attitudes toward social power}]{Attitudes toward social power}
				

